Top ten schools by mean

I want to find the average math proficiency in each school.

I create a new dataframe called mean_math_proficiency_by_school

  • I first drop the eight rows with NA values on the percent_proficient column (listed in the previous output). Because I have no way of knowing what the math scores might be for these eight observations, and I am reporting descriptive statistics, it would be unwise to impute values for the missing observations.

  • I group by building name and filter for “All Students”

  • I create a column called mean_percent_proficient that lists the mean percent of students who are proficient or higher in math at each school. The means are weighted by number_tested to account for different class sizes.

  • I arrange mean_percent_proficient in descending order to show the highest values first.

  • I use head() to view the top ten schools.

mean_math_proficiency_by_school = student_scores_math %>%
  drop_na(percent_proficient) %>%
  group_by(building_name) %>%
  filter(subgroup == "All Students") %>%
  summarise(mean_percent_proficient = weighted.mean(percent_proficient, number_tested)) %>%
  arrange(desc(mean_percent_proficient))

head(mean_math_proficiency_by_school, 10)

I multiply the mean_percent_proficient column by 100 to get the percentages and take another look at the top ten.

mean_math_proficiency_by_school = mean_math_proficiency_by_school %>%

I create a new dataframe called top_ten_all_data by filtering the student_scores_math dataframe for all observations where the building name is equal to any of the ten building names in the top_ten_schools_in_math_proficiency dataframe.

I then filter top_ten_all_data to include only the “All Students” subgroup

Next, I create box plots of each of the top ten schools to view outliers.

top_ten_all_data = student_scores_math %>%
  filter(building_name %in% top_ten_schools_in_math_proficiency$building_name)

# box plots
top_ten_boxplots = top_ten_all_data %>%
  filter(subgroup == "All Students")
  
ggplot(top_ten_all_data, aes(x = building_name, y = percent_proficient)) +
  geom_boxplot()

I see that three schools have outliers, and two schools have outliers that are far above the average scores. These outliers are individual grade levels within a school. It could be the case that these teachers are doing something that causes their students to score high on math proficiency exams. This could be something interesting to look into later, but for the purpose of this project, these outliers are causing a biased estimate of the performance of the school overall. It might be better to look at the median instead of the mean.

Top ten schools by median

I use the same code as before, but this time I am looking at median instead of mean.

median_math_proficiency_by_school = student_scores_math %>%
  drop_na(percent_proficient) %>%
  group_by(building_name) %>%
  filter(subgroup == "All Students") %>%
  summarise(median_percent_proficient = weighted.median(percent_proficient, number_tested)) %>%
  arrange(desc(median_percent_proficient))

It looks like there are more schools in effectiveness_snapshot than in the scores data. Because of this, I will perform a left join, joining effectiveness_snapshot to student_scores_math by the name of the school.

joined_data = left_join(student_scores_math, effectiveness_snapshot,
                         by = c('building_name' = 'location'))

Checking for missing data

I already checked to insure there was no missing data on the total column, and every school on the student scores list should have a match on the educator effectiveness snapshot list. Therefore, there should not be any rows with missing data on the total column after the join.

I check to make sure this is the case by viewing the unique building names of joined_data where the total column is NA.

I use unique() because I don’t want to return the same school a bunch of times if one school has missing data.

unique(subset(joined_data, is.na(joined_data$total))[, "building_name"])
## [1] "All Buildings"                     "Carstens Elementary-Middle School"
## [3] "Pulaski Elementary-Middle School"

It looks like there are three building names that do not have data on the total column. “All Buildings” is not a school, so I can drop that from the dataframe. The other two schools should have values. There might be subtle name differences or errors in spelling between the two data sets. I will investigate further.

I index locations from the effectiveness_snapshot dataframe that are similar to “Pulaski”

effectiveness_snapshot[effectiveness_snapshot$location %like% "Pulaski", "location"]
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##   location                  
##   <chr>                     
## 1 Pulaski Elem-Middle School

I see that in the effectiveness_snapshot dataframe the word “Elementary” is abriviated. This is the source of our problems.

In effectiveness_snapshot, I change the name from “Pulaski Elem-Middle School” to “Pulaski Elementary-Middle School” to match the student scores data.

effectiveness_snapshot[effectiveness_snapshot$location == "Pulaski Elem-Middle School", "location"] = "Pulaski Elementary-Middle School"

I use the same process with the second school:

I index locations from the effectiveness_snapshot dataframe that are similar to “Carstens”

effectiveness_snapshot[effectiveness_snapshot$location %like% "Carstens", "location"]
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##   location                   
##   <chr>                      
## 1 Carstens Elem-Middle School

I see we have the same problem with this school.

I apply the same solution.

effectiveness_snapshot[effectiveness_snapshot$location == "Carstens Elem-Middle School", "location"] = "Carstens Elementary-Middle School"

Now that the names have been changed, I perform the same left join again.

joined_data = left_join(student_scores_math, effectiveness_snapshot,
                        by = c('building_name' = 'location'))

I use the same code as before to make sure the changes worked and that there are not schools with missing data on the total column.

unique(subset(joined_data, is.na(joined_data$total))[, "building_name"])
## [1] "All Buildings"

I drop “All Buildings” because it is not a school.

joined_data = joined_data[joined_data$building_name != "All Buildings", ]

I check once more to make sure the changes worked.

unique(subset(joined_data, is.na(joined_data$total))[, "building_name"])
## character(0)

There are no missing building names. We can now move on.

Segmenting based on subgroup

I want to view the relationship between math proficiency for all students and educator effectiveness at the school level, but I also would like to look at different subgroups. It could be the case that the relationship between math proficiency and educator effectiveness is different for different subgroups.

I first want to take a quick glance at some boxplots for all of the data to get an idea of how many outliers I am dealing with.

I create a graph with a boxplot for each school.

joined_boxplots = joined_data %>%
  filter(subgroup == "All Students")
  
ggplot(joined_boxplots, aes(x = building_name, y = percent_proficient)) +
  geom_boxplot()

There seem to be quite a few outliers for several schools. I will continue to use weighted (by class size) median as an average measure for each school.

I create a dataframe with the median math proficiency in each school and the proportion of teachers in each school who are “effective or more” using the “All Students” subgroup and view the first five observations.

median_math_proficiency_all_students = joined_data %>%
  drop_na(percent_proficient) %>%
  group_by(building_name) %>%
  filter(subgroup == "All Students") %>%
  summarise(median_percent_proficient = weighted.median(percent_proficient, number_tested), 
            effective_percent = mean(effective_or_more_percent))

Regression

I thought it would be interesting to fit a linear regression model to this data because the interpretation of the slope will provide me with a way of predicting math proficiency at the school level based on teacher effectiveness.

I first transform the proportions to percentages for better interpretation.

median_math_proficiency_all_students = median_math_proficiency_all_students %>%
  mutate(median_percent_proficient = (median_percent_proficient*100), 
         effective_percent = (effective_percent*100))

I fit a simple linear regression model using the data from median_math_proficiency_all_students, setting median_percent_proficient as the outcome variable and effective_percent as the predictor variable.

all_students = lm(median_percent_proficient ~ effective_percent, data = median_math_proficiency_all_students)
all_students
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = median_percent_proficient ~ effective_percent, data = median_math_proficiency_all_students)
## 
## Coefficients:
##       (Intercept)  effective_percent  
##          -46.0754             0.6041
print(summary(all_students))
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = median_percent_proficient ~ effective_percent, data = median_math_proficiency_all_students)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -14.337  -7.302  -3.101   3.356  47.813

## F-statistic: 4.346 on 1 and 66 DF,  p-value: 0.04097

The slope of this model is about 0.6. For every one percent increase in educator effectiveness, we can expect to see a 0.6 percent increase in math proficiency. However, I want to investigate model fit a bit more before I read too far into this interpretation.

I obtain three plots:

  • A plot of residuals vs fitted: This plot indicates heteroscedasticity.

  • A Q-Q plot: This plot indicates that residuals are not normally distributed (positive skew).

  • A scale location plot: Residuals are not randomly scattered with equal variability at all fitted values.

autoplot(all_students, which = 1:3)

It looks like this regression model is a poor fit. I will not use it in the email/report.

Email to my manager

Dear [name of manager]

I hope this email finds you well.

This email is in response to your recent inquiry about the relationship between the math proficiency of a school’s students and the effectiveness of its teachers at the school level.

I looked at the relationship between math proficiency for all students and educator effectiveness (percent of educators in a school who are either effective or highly effective) and found a correlation of about 0.25 – there is a weak positive relationship between these two variables. In other words, schools that have a higher percentage of effective or highly effective teachers will also have a higher percentage of students who are proficient in math.

However, I would stress two things: 1) This relationship is weak. 2) This is not necessarily a causal relationship. We can’t say for certain that effective teachers cause students to be more proficient in math. It could be the case that students with high math ability and teachers with effective teaching strategies simply end up at the same school together, and students with lower math ability and teachers with less effective teaching strategies simply end up at the same school together.

In addition to looking at all students in a school. I also looked at several subgroups in isolation to see if the relationship between the math proficiency and the effectiveness of teachers changes based on the subgroup. I found that for males, females, and economically disadvantaged students the relationship is the same as it was when looking at all students together. However, for students who are not economically disadvantaged, I found that there was a stronger relationship between math proficiency and teacher effectiveness (a correlation of about 0.4), which I would classify as a moderate relationship. For English language learner students, I found that there were two schools that have relatively high math proficiency rates (Davidson Elementary-Middle School and Burton International School). However, if you remove these two schools, there seems to be no relationship between the remaining schools’ math proficiency rates and teacher effectiveness.

In short, here is a summary of the results:

  • All students: weak relationship (correlation of 0.25)

  • Males: weak relationship (correlation of 0.26)

  • Females: weak relationship (correlation of 0.24)

  • Economically disadvantaged students: weak relationship (correlation of 0.24)

  • Not economically disadvantaged students: moderate relationship (correlation of 0.4)

  • English language learner students (after removing two schools): No relationship

The conclusion that the district can draw from this analysis is that there is a weak relationship between the math proficiency of a school’s students and the effectiveness of its teachers at the school level. For students who are not economically disadvantaged, this relationship is considerably stronger.

I hope this helps! Please don’t hesitate to reach out if you have additional questions or need clarification on any of the results.

Best, [my name]
